Background

This report provides a brief summary of the weekly ensemble forecast from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub based on forecasts submitted on April 12, 2021. In collaboration with the US CDC, our team aggregates COVID-19 forecasts from dozens of teams around the globe. Typically on Wednesday of each week, a summary of the weeks forecasts from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub appear on the official CDC COVID-19 forecasting page.

Every week, teams submit their forecasts to the COVID-19 Forecast Hub. This past week, 53 models were submitted.

Each Monday evening or Tuesday morning, we combine the most recent forecasts from each team into a single ensemble forecast of reported COVID-19 cases at the county, state, and national level and deaths at the state and national level. At the moment, we only generate ensemble forecasts for four weeks into the future, as the available evidence suggests that models are less accurate at longer forecast horizons.

An archive of weekly reports from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub can be found at this page.

COVID-19 Forecasts

National level

This week, our ensemble combined forecasts from 43 different models.

At the national level, the ensemble model predicts that weekly totals of observed deaths in each of the next four weeks will be between 5,700 and 6,000 deaths with around 585,900 deaths by May 08 (95% prediction interval: 574,081 - 597,853).

For the week ending May 08, the ensemble forecasts that reported COVID-19 deaths in the US will be between 2,500 and 10,500 (95% prediction interval: 2,541 - 10,545) and COVID-19 cases in the US will be between 263,600 and 850,500 (95% prediction interval: 263,635 - 850,451).

For May 10, 2021 COVID-19 daily hospitalizations in the US will be between 2,500 and 9,300 (95% prediction interval: 2,477 - 9,294).

You can explore the full set of models, including their forecasts for past weeks online at our interactive forecast visualization.

State level

The ensemble model estimates that 27 states and territories of the US have a greater than 50% chance of having more deaths in the next two weeks compared to the past two weeks.The model forecasts that 7 states and territories have a greater than 75% chance of an increase over the next two weeks (Alaska, Michigan, Minnesota, North Dakota, American Samoa, Northern Mariana Islands, Virgin Islands).

The sortable and searchable table below shows the total number of reported COVID-19 deaths at the US level and by state over the last two weeks (ending Saturday, April 10, 2021) and the forecasted counts for the subsequent two weeks (ending April 24, 2021).

Looking at the rates allows for easier comparison across states, where you can see which states have had or are predicted to have proportionally higher rates in comparison to other states.

When interpreting probability of an increase, its important to note that the increase or decrease is relative to the location-specific recent observed incidence, which varies across locations.
